Why Jerome Powell must go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as head of the US Federal Reserve – that is, to the possibly most powerful position within the global economy?
A wrong decision here can have serious consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to regulate the banking system appropriately, thereby setting the stage for the worst global economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the political decision-makers' response to it had far-reaching political consequences; they exacerbated inequality and fostered a lasting sense of dissatisfaction among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are a number of clichés as to why the current Federal Reserve chair Jerome Powell should be confirmed in office.
It would be a proof of bipartisan support.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
Someone with experience would be needed to guide us through the recovery following the pandemic.
And so on.
Exactly the same arguments I had already heard 25 years ago, when I was chairman of the economic advisory staff to US President Bill Clinton and the confirmation of Greenspan in office was the topic.
They were enough to convince Clinton, and the country paid a heavy price for his decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little attention to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and denied him a second term, despite Volcker having tamed inflation.
Reagan owed Volcker a lot, but he pursued deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, a follower of Ayn Rand.
In economic policy, careful assessment and sensitivity to conflicting objectives are required.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that the markets are efficient, stable, fair, and shaped by competition on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the United States always represented clearly articulated, but distinctly different viewpoints on these issues (at least until the Republicans fell into the populist frenzy).
From my perspective, the Democrats are rightly concerned about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis has shown that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
In addition, we know that traditionally, only in tight labor markets are marginalized groups integrated into the economy and wage disparities reduced.
The coming years are likely to be a test for every U.S. Federal Reserve chairman.
The United States is already facing difficult decisions on how to deal with inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially minor issues stemming from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed view the unemployment rate of African Americans, which has not yet returned to its pre-pandemic level?
Would raising interest rates (and thus an increase in unemployment) be worse than the illness itself?
Equally important: While the mispricing of mortgage-backed securities played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of a stronger and more pervasive mispricing associated with climate-related assets.
What should the Fed do in this regard?
Powell is not the man of the hour.
First, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump and thereby risked the financial health of our world.
And yet, he still hesitates to take action regarding the climate risk, although other central bankers around the world have already declared it the central issue of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues are not within the mandate of the Fed, but he would be wrong.
It is part of the Fed's mandate to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater threat to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record in this area suggests that he has never experienced a bad merger.
Such laxity is the last thing the economy currently needs.
A glaring lack of competition and the absence of adequate regulation already allow excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses, and give dominant actors more room to exploit others.
Some commentators credit Powell for the Fed's response to the pandemic.
Yet every student in their second year would have known that during a recession, one must not tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT has argued, Powell does not feel particularly strongly committed to full employment.
In contrast: Powell's record as a member of the U.S. Federal Reserve Board regarding the tightening of monetary policy over the past decade has been marked by a series of misjudgments dating back to the "Taper Tantrum" of 2013.
Although many Fed observers insist that inequality is not the Federal Reserve's concern, it is a fact that the bank's policies have significant distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as an early rate hike can stifle growth, a weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for stronger concentrations of market power.
And finally, the recent scandal involving stock trading by senior Fed officials has undermined confidence in the leadership of the central bank.
My concerns have long been about Powell's apparently lack of awareness of conflicts of interest, including in the administration of certain Fed programs in response to the pandemic.
After four years of Trump having already weakened trust in U.S. institutions, there is now a real risk that trust in the integrity of the central bank will suffer further.
No Fed official should need an ethics officer to decide when certain stock trades would appear inappropriate.
The Fed resembles the U.S. Supreme Court in certain respects.
This is supposed to stand above politics, but by the time of Bush v. Gore, we know that is not the case.
Trump has made it clear to everyone who still had doubts.
The Fed is supposed to be independent, yet Powell and Greenspan have clearly shown that this is also not the case by following the deregulation agenda of their party.
Yet while the central bank's board makes important decisions that influence all aspects of the economy, power has traditionally concentrated in the hands of the central bank chair—much more strongly than with the chief justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the central bank chair who decides which issues come up for discussion and which topics are postponed or pushed forward.
The climate issue is just one example where it is extremely important who sits at the head of the table.
The United States need a central bank that genuinely commits to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competitive financial sector.
Who believes that we can rely on unregulated markets or that regulation has already gone too far lacks insight.
We neither need an ideologue like Greenspan nor a Wall Street-friendly lawyer like Powell.
Someone is needed who has deep knowledge of economics and who shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There are undoubtedly many people who meet these conditions.
But Biden doesn't have to look far to find someone who has already demonstrated his skills.
Lael Brainard is already sitting on the Federal Reserve Board, where she has demonstrated her competence and gained the trust of the markets – without compromising her values.
Biden can have both: a female central bank chair who maintains continuity and does not unsettle the markets, but who shares his economic and social program.
